---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const siteOrigin = Astro.site?.toString().replace(/\/$/, "") ?? "";

const aboutSchema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "AboutPage",
    name: "About Carpool",
    url: `${siteOrigin}/about`,
    mainEntity: {
      "@type": "Organization",
      name: "Carpool",
      url: siteOrigin,
      foundingLocation: { "@type": "Country", name: "Pakistan" },
      description:
        "A free, zero-commission carpool noticeboard for daily commuters in Pakistan. Built and maintained solo.",
    },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="About Carpool — built solo for Pakistani daily commuters"
  description="Why Carpool exists, what it promises, and who runs it. A free, zero-commission noticeboard for daily commuters in Karachi, Lahore, Islamabad and beyond."
  canonical="/about"
  schema={aboutSchema}
>
  <article class="about">
    <header class="about-head">
      <span class="kicker">About</span>
      <h1>Built solo, run for commuters.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Carpool is a free noticeboard for people who already commute the same
        route every day. Drivers post where they're driving and when. Riders
        search by their own pickup and destination, then contact the driver
        directly. There's no app, no middleman, no commission, and no account
        required to browse.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="block">
      <h2>Why I built it</h2>
      <p>
        Daily commuting in Pakistan is expensive. Ride-hailing apps are great
        for occasional trips, but at five or six rides a week, the cost adds
        up fast — and the apps weren't built to put two strangers heading the
        same way together for a recurring journey.
      </p>
      <p>
        Carpools already happen informally — neighbours, coworkers, school
        parents. The problem isn't whether people want to share a ride; it's
        finding someone already going your exact way at your exact time. That
        coordination almost always happens through who-you-know — WhatsApp
        groups, building boards, a friend-of-a-friend. If you don't know
        anyone driving your route, you're out of luck.
      </p>
      <p>
        Carpool is the public board. Anyone driving a regular route can post
        it. Anyone needing a ride on a similar route can find it and reach
        out — directly, on WhatsApp or by phone.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="block">
      <h2>The promise</h2>
      <ul class="promise">
        <li>
          <strong>Zero commission.</strong> Whatever you charge or contribute
          for fuel is between you and the other person. We never take a cut
          and never will.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Free to post, free to browse.</strong> No subscription, no
          paywall, no premium tier.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No account needed to search.</strong> You only sign in when
          you want to publish a ride as a driver.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Your phone number stays yours.</strong> It's only visible
          on a listing you've chosen to publish — never sold, never used for
          marketing.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Female-only carpools are first-class.</strong> Drivers and
          riders can both filter for them. Safety is a feature, not an
          afterthought.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="block">
      <h2>Who runs it</h2>
      <p>
        Carpool is built and maintained by a single developer — me, working
        on it on the side because the daily commute problem is one I live
        with. There's no team, no investors, no growth quotas. That keeps
        the product simple and keeps it free.
      </p>
      <p>
        If something on the site is broken or annoying, the email below
        lands directly in my inbox. Same goes for ideas, route suggestions,
        and "you should add my city" requests.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="block">
      <h2>How it stays free</h2>
      <p>
        Hosting and tile costs are tiny — the site runs on Netlify's free
        tier and uses OpenStreetMap-derived map data with no paid API keys.
        If volume ever grows enough that hosting costs become real, I'll add
        an optional supporter tier before I'd ever charge a commission. The
        marketplace itself stays free, always.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="block contact">
      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>
        Email <a href="mailto:hello@carpool.high-score.dev">hello@carpool.high-score.dev</a>
        — feedback, bugs, route ideas, partnerships, everything.
      </p>
      <div class="about-actions">
        <a href="/drivers/register" class="btn btn-primary">Offer a ride</a>
        <a href="/drivers" class="btn btn-ghost">Find a ride</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about {
    max-width: 44rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .about-head {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  .kicker {
    display: inline-block;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--amber);
    margin-bottom: 0.55rem;
  }
  .about-head h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3rem);
    font-weight: 800;
  }
  .lede {
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
  .block {
    padding: 1.8rem 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .block h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.85rem;
  }
  .block p {
    margin: 0 0 0.85rem;
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }
  .block p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .promise {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.85rem;
  }
  .promise li {
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }
  .promise strong {
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .contact .about-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    margin-top: 1.1rem;
  }
</style>
